#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:32
msgid "If you get an error checkout :ref:`installation issues`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:37
msgid "Our first test run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:39
msgid "Let's create a first test file with a simple test function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:41
msgid ""
"# content of test_sample.py\n"
"def func(x):\n"
"    return x + 1\n"
"\n"
"def test_answer():\n"
"    assert func(3) == 5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:48
msgid "That's it. You can execute the test function now::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:50
msgid ""
"$ py.test\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_sample.py F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_answer ________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_answer():\n"
">       assert func(3) == 5\n"
"E       assert 4 == 5\n"
"E        +  where 4 = func(3)\n"
"\n"
"test_sample.py:5: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:69
msgid ""
"We got a failure report because our little ``func(3)`` call did not return "
"``5``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:73
msgid ""
"You can simply use the ``assert`` statement for asserting test "
"expectations.  pytest's :ref:`assert introspection` will intelligently "
"report intermediate values of the assert expression freeing you from the "
"need to learn the many names of `JUnit legacy methods`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:83
msgid "Running multiple tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:85
msgid ""
"``pytest`` will run all files in the current directory and its "
"subdirectories of the form test_*.py or \\*_test.py. More generally, it "
"follows :ref:`standard test discovery rules <test discovery>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:89
msgid "Asserting that a certain exception is raised"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:91
msgid ""
"If you want to assert that some code raises an exception you can use the "
"``raises`` helper::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:94
msgid ""
"# content of test_sysexit.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"def f():\n"
"    raise SystemExit(1)\n"
"\n"
"def test_mytest():\n"
"    with pytest.raises(SystemExit):\n"
"        f()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:103
msgid "Running it with, this time in \"quiet\" reporting mode::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:105
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_sysexit.py\n"
".\n"
"1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:110
msgid "Grouping multiple tests in a class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:112
msgid ""
"Once you start to have more than a few tests it often makes sense to group "
"tests logically, in classes and modules.  Let's write a class containing two "
"tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:116
msgid ""
"# content of test_class.py\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    def test_one(self):\n"
"        x = \"this\"\n"
"        assert 'h' in x\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
"        x = \"hello\"\n"
"        assert hasattr(x, 'check')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:126
msgid ""
"The two tests are found because of the standard :ref:`test discovery`. There "
"is no need to subclass anything.  We can simply run the module by passing "
"its filename::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:130
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_class.py\n"
".F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ TestClass.test_two ________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_class.TestClass object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_two(self):\n"
"        x = \"hello\"\n"
">       assert hasattr(x, 'check')\n"
"E       assert hasattr('hello', 'check')\n"
"\n"
"test_class.py:8: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed, 1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:145
msgid ""
"The first test passed, the second failed. Again we can easily see the "
"intermediate values used in the assertion, helping us to understand the "
"reason for the failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:150
msgid "Going functional: requesting a unique temporary directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:152
msgid ""
"For functional tests one often needs to create some files and pass them to "
"application objects.  pytest provides :ref:`builtinfixtures` which allow to "
"request arbitrary resources, for example a unique temporary directory::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:157
msgid ""
"# content of test_tmpdir.py\n"
"def test_needsfiles(tmpdir):\n"
"    print (tmpdir)\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:162
msgid ""
"We list the name ``tmpdir`` in the test function signature and ``pytest`` "
"will lookup and call a fixture factory to create the resource before "
"performing the test function call.  Let's just run it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:166
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q test_tmpdir.py\n"
"F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_needsfiles ________\n"
"\n"
"tmpdir = local('PYTEST_TMPDIR/test_needsfiles0')\n"
"\n"
"    def test_needsfiles(tmpdir):\n"
"        print (tmpdir)\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_tmpdir.py:3: AssertionError\n"
"--------------------------- Captured stdout call "
"---------------------------\n"
"PYTEST_TMPDIR/test_needsfiles0\n"
"1 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/getting-started.rst:183
msgid ""
"Before the test runs, a unique-per-test-invocation temporary directory was "
"created.  More info at :ref:`tmpdir handling`."
msgstr ""

